<collectingCountry box="[553,659,152,176]" name="Morocco" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[670,756,151,176]" name="Tunisia" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
, Lybia, 
<collectingCountry box="[845,917,152,176]" name="Egypt" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Egypt</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,350,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Pollen hosts.</emphasis>
Probably oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName box="[629,746,188,213]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[629,746,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Frankenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[762,932,188,213]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Frankeniaceae</taxonomicName>
): all 
<number box="[986,1000,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" value="9.0">9</number>
pollen loads (
<number box="[1163,1177,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" value="3.0">3</number>
localities, 
<number box="[1301,1315,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" value="2.0">2</number>
countries) analyzed so far consisted of 
<taxonomicName box="[476,593,223,248]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[476,593,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Frankenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pollen, and males of 
<taxonomicName box="[840,972,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartliebi">
<emphasis box="[840,972,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">H. hartliebi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were observed patrolling near flowering plants of 
<taxonomicName box="[255,479,260,285]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Frankeniaceae" genus="Frankenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis box="[255,371,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Frankenia</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[414,479,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">laevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[619,702,260,285]" name="Tunisia" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[717,824,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 5. 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1644,1666]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,483,1619]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,483,1619]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 5. 1 – 3: Sandy slope at the shore of a salt lake near Medenine in southern Tunisia (Fig. 1), where females of Hoplitis minima collected pollen on the flowers of Zygophyllum album (Fig. 2) and males of Hoplitis hartliebi patrolled flowers of Frankenia cf. laevis (Fig. 3). 4: Hoplitis minima, head of female. 5: Hoplitis jordanica, terga 4 – 7 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229654/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Figs. 1, 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,464]" box="[199,514,295,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,295,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Nesting biology.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,332,357]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Note.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[272,405,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartliebi">
<emphasis box="[272,405,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">H. hartliebi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[596,697,333,356]" name="Morocco" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Morocco</collectingCountry>
so far only from four females collected near Mhamid. In these females, the distance between lateral ocellus and preoccipital ridge is slightly longer (about 
<number box="[1185,1219,368,392]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" value="1.7">1.7</number>
x as long as ocellar diameter) compared to that of females from 
<collectingCountry box="[641,724,404,429]" name="Tunisia" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
(
<number box="[739,827,404,429]" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" value="1.55" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.6</number>
x). 
<collectingCountry box="[860,891,404,428]" name="American Samoa" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">As</collectingCountry>
no males of 
<taxonomicName box="[1033,1163,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hartliebi">
<emphasis box="[1033,1163,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">H. hartliebi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have ever been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,255,440,463]" name="Morocco" pageId="6" pageNumber="307">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, it cannot be excluded with certainty that the Moroccon specimens belong to a still undescribed species.
</paragraph>
